snippet: Beyond a forceful repudiation of President Obama, there was little uniformity on just what Republican voters wanted from their party’s new Senate majority.
abstract: Interviews with Republican voters from across the country reveal that there is little uniformity on just what they want from Republican majority in the next Congress; beyond any specific policy, primary wish of Republican voters is cooperation to end political gridlock.

byline.contributor: Reporting was contributed by Alan Blinder from Sherwood, Ark., Julie Turkewitz from Denver, Kayla Gahagan from Rapid City, S.D., Ann Hinga Klein from Des Moines, Jonathan Katz from Raleigh, N.C., and Daniel Heyman from Charleston, W.V.

lead_paragraph: Beyond a forceful repudiation of President Obama, there was little uniformity on just what Republican voters wanted from their party’s new Senate majority.

headline.main: Republican Voters Want to Get Things Done, but Differ on Priorities
headline.print_headline: Republican Voters See a Signal Opportunity, but Differ on Priorities
